<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="21.[264,1325,761,1870]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,439,1041,1067]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Forewing vein RS+M developed, head and thorax reddish brown, and lateral margins of metasomal tergum 1 almost parallel.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="23" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="21.[264,1325,761,1870]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,464,1121,1147]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Description.</emphasis>
FEMALE. Colour. Body generally reddish brown except for small black spot anterior to ocelli; propodeum, metanotum and metasomal tergum 1 brown (
<figureCitation box="[1218,1307,1162,1188]" captionStart="FIGURE 37–49. 37" captionStartId="74.[264,367,1770,1794]" captionTargetBox="[316,1273,318,1748]" captionTargetId="figure-43@74.[313,1273,308,1748]" captionTargetPageId="74" captionText="FIGURE 37–49. 37. Lateral view of antenna. 38–39. Last six flagellomeres in lateral view. 40–44. Dorsal view of mesosoma. 45–49. Lateral view of mesosoma." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5071190" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5071190/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Fig. 42</figureCitation>
), and face and clypeus dark straw coloured (as in 
<figureCitation box="[827,911,1202,1228]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–24. 13–22" captionStartId="72.[264,382,1790,1814]" captionTargetBox="[318,1260,326,1763]" captionTargetId="figure-36@72.[313,1273,326,1766]" captionTargetPageId="72" captionText="FIGURES 13–24. 13–22. Frontal view of head. Code: “a” ventral edge of clypeus. 23–24. Dorsal view of head." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5071184" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5071184/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
) (metasomal tergum 3 is as pale as preceding tergum, but appears brown due to telescoping of the more apical segments under it). Appendages straw coloured except apical third of flagellum fading to brown (
<figureCitation box="[1232,1306,1282,1308]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–5" captionStartId="70.[264,382,1793,1817]" captionTargetBox="[313,1273,333,1772]" captionTargetId="figure-39@70.[313,1273,332,1772]" captionTargetPageId="70" captionText="FIGURES 1–5. Habitus with frontal view of head. Codes: “a” clypeal colour; “b” metatibial colour; “c” metacoxal colour; “d” forewing colour; “e” mesoscutal colour." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5071180" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5071180/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). Forewing clear except for two dark coloured bands aligned with 1 
<superScript attach="left" box="[1052,1063,1322,1336]" fontSize="6" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">st</superScript>
discal cell and below apical 0.7 of stigma (apical band fading to clear toward apex) (
<figureCitation box="[998,1069,1364,1390]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–5" captionStartId="70.[264,382,1793,1817]" captionTargetBox="[313,1273,333,1772]" captionTargetId="figure-39@70.[313,1273,332,1772]" captionTargetPageId="70" captionText="FIGURES 1–5. Habitus with frontal view of head. Codes: “a” clypeal colour; “b” metatibial colour; “c” metacoxal colour; “d” forewing colour; “e” mesoscutal colour." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5071180" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5071180/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
); radial cell clear, but surrounded by apical dark band. Wing veins light straw coloured, but brown on 1M, 1cu­a, RS R1 and RS+M and on apical 0.7 of stigma.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[264,1325,761,1870]" lastBlockId="22.[264,1325,284,1876]" lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="23" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Structure. Flagellum with 13 flagellomeres. Clypeus with two short and sharp teeth along anterior margin near middle (as in 
<figureCitation box="[750,837,1524,1550]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–24. 13–22" captionStartId="72.[264,382,1790,1814]" captionTargetBox="[318,1260,326,1763]" captionTargetId="figure-36@72.[313,1273,326,1766]" captionTargetPageId="72" captionText="FIGURES 13–24. 13–22. Frontal view of head. Code: “a” ventral edge of clypeus. 23–24. Dorsal view of head." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5071184" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5071184/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
). Length of gena behind eye 1.1 times as long as length of eye. Height of eye 1.8 times as long as minimum distance between inner eye margins. Maximum width of head behind eyes subequal to maximum head width at eye level. Occipital carina either absent in dorsal 0.3 or abruptly reduced to a trace in dorsal 0.3. Mesoscutellar fovea about 2–3 times as wide as long and with 4 septa (as in 
<figureCitation box="[264,354,1724,1750]" captionStart="FIGURE 37–49. 37" captionStartId="74.[264,367,1770,1794]" captionTargetBox="[316,1273,318,1748]" captionTargetId="figure-43@74.[313,1273,308,1748]" captionTargetPageId="74" captionText="FIGURE 37–49. 37. Lateral view of antenna. 38–39. Last six flagellomeres in lateral view. 40–44. Dorsal view of mesosoma. 45–49. Lateral view of mesosoma." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5071190" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5071190/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Fig. 40</figureCitation>
). Metasomal tergum 1 with lateral margins almost parallel (posterior margin 1.3 times as wide as narrowest width near base), long (length 2.8 times maximum width), and almost meeting ventrally in anterior 0.3. Radial cell near stigma, and forewing vein RS+M developed (as in 
<figureCitation box="[462,548,1844,1870]" captionStart="FIGURES 50–58. 50–52" captionStartId="75.[264,382,1790,1814]" captionTargetBox="[313,1268,326,1765]" captionTargetId="figure-37@75.[313,1273,326,1766]" captionTargetPageId="75" captionText="FIGURES 50–58. 50–52. Forewing. 53–54. Basal and subbasal cells of forewing. 55–58. Radial cell and stigma of forewing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5071192" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5071192/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Fig. 51</figureCitation>
). Basal cell of forewing with 0–3 setae, clearly less densely setose than 1 
<superScript attach="left" box="[341,352,284,298]" fontSize="6" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">st</superScript>
discal cell (as in 
<figureCitation box="[580,671,287,313]" captionStart="FIGURES 50–58. 50–52" captionStartId="75.[264,382,1790,1814]" captionTargetBox="[313,1268,326,1765]" captionTargetId="figure-37@75.[313,1273,326,1766]" captionTargetPageId="75" captionText="FIGURES 50–58. 50–52. Forewing. 53–54. Basal and subbasal cells of forewing. 55–58. Radial cell and stigma of forewing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5071192" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5071192/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Fig. 53</figureCitation>
). Veins 1CU and 1m­cu not usually developed, or if developed then 1 
<superScript attach="left" box="[464,475,327,341]" fontSize="6" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">st</superScript>
discal cell almost triangular because vein 1m­cu about 0.2 times as long as vein RS+M. Radial cell 0.5 as long as width of stigma (as in 
<figureCitation box="[1024,1112,370,396]" captionStart="FIGURES 50–58. 50–52" captionStartId="75.[264,382,1790,1814]" captionTargetBox="[313,1268,326,1765]" captionTargetId="figure-37@75.[313,1273,326,1766]" captionTargetPageId="75" captionText="FIGURES 50–58. 50–52. Forewing. 53–54. Basal and subbasal cells of forewing. 55–58. Radial cell and stigma of forewing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5071192" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5071192/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Fig. 55</figureCitation>
). Subbasal cell of hind wing narrow: vein 1M 3.0 times as long as vein cu­a (as in 
<figureCitation box="[1020,1107,410,436]" captionStart="FIGURES 59–66. 59–63" captionStartId="76.[264,382,1790,1814]" captionTargetBox="[313,1273,329,1763]" captionTargetId="figure-36@76.[313,1273,326,1766]" captionTargetPageId="76" captionText="FIGURES 59–66. 59–63. Radial cell and stigma of forewing. 64. Hind wing. 65–66. Basal and subbasal cells of hind wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5071194" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5071194/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Fig. 65</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[264,1325,284,1876]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
Sculpture. Punctures on vertex, frons and mesoscutum about 
<quantity box="[1086,1169,450,476]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" unit="mm" value="10.0">10 µm</quantity>
in diameter (similar to diameter of ommatidia). Punctures 
<quantity box="[811,931,490,516]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" unit="mm" value="25.0" valueMax="30.0" valueMin="20.0">20–30 µm</quantity>
apart on vertex and frons, 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" metricValueMax="6.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" unit="mm" value="45.0" valueMax="60.0" valueMin="30.0">30–60 µm</quantity>
apart on mesoscutum, and 
<quantity box="[665,792,530,556]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" metricValueMax="8.0" metricValueMin="6.0" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" unit="mm" value="70.0" valueMax="80.0" valueMin="60.0">60–80 µm</quantity>
apart on mesopleuron. Clypeus generally glabrous except for row of long setae along anterior margin. Notaulus not outlined in anterior half (as in 
<figureCitation box="[487,573,610,636]" captionStart="FIGURE 37–49. 37" captionStartId="74.[264,367,1770,1794]" captionTargetBox="[316,1273,318,1748]" captionTargetId="figure-43@74.[313,1273,308,1748]" captionTargetPageId="74" captionText="FIGURE 37–49. 37. Lateral view of antenna. 38–39. Last six flagellomeres in lateral view. 40–44. Dorsal view of mesosoma. 45–49. Lateral view of mesosoma." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5071190" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5071190/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Fig. 41</figureCitation>
). Metasomal tergum 1 with about 6 longitudinal ridges.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[264,1325,284,1876]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Frons and anterior region of vertex with very lightly impressed meshes. Mesoscutum with transverse, barely outlined, ridges medially in posterior one quarter. Mesopleuron with weakly outlined parallel ridges slanted downward. Remaining body surfaces smooth.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[264,1325,284,1876]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">MALE. Colour. As in female, except propodeum, metanotum and metasomal tergum 1 as pale as body.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[264,1325,284,1876]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
Structure. Clypeal anterior margin without teeth near middle (
<figureCitation box="[1049,1137,850,876]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–24. 13–22" captionStartId="72.[264,382,1790,1814]" captionTargetBox="[318,1260,326,1763]" captionTargetId="figure-36@72.[313,1273,326,1766]" captionTargetPageId="72" captionText="FIGURES 13–24. 13–22. Frontal view of head. Code: “a” ventral edge of clypeus. 23–24. Dorsal view of head." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5071184" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5071184/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
). Height of eye 1.2 times as long as minimum distance between inner eye margins. Tergum 1 of metasoma with sides little divergent (maximum width 1.4 times as long as minimum width), and long (length 2.6 times maximum width). Otherwise structure and sculpture as in female.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[264,1325,284,1876]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,531,1009,1035]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Taxonomic notes.</emphasis>
This species belongs to the 
<taxonomicName authority="(Ashmead)" baseAuthorityName="Ashmead" baseAuthorityYear="1887" box="[879,1209,1010,1036]" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Leiophron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maculipennis">
<emphasis box="[879,1069,1010,1035]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">L. maculipennis</emphasis>
(Ashmead)
</taxonomicName>
group as defined by 
<bibRefCitation author="Loan, C. C." box="[399,561,1050,1076]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" pagination="821 - 860" refId="ref42379" refString="Loan, C. C. (1974 a) The North American species of Leiophron Nees, 1818 and Peristenus Foerster, 1862 (Hymenoptera: Braconidae, Euphorinae) including the description of 31 new species. Le Naturaliste Canadien, 101, 821 - 860." type="journal article" year="1974">Loan (1974a)</bibRefCitation>
, based on the shared presence of forewing veins RS+M and the lack of forewing veins 1CU, m­cu and 2RS. Within this group, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Goulet &amp; Mason" authorityYear="2006" box="[1012,1145,1090,1115]" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Leiophron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis box="[1012,1145,1090,1115]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">L. australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is closest to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Ashmead" baseAuthorityYear="1887" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Leiophron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maculipennis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">L. maculipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
because both species share the reduced number of flagellomeres (12 or 
<quantity box="[1261,1321,1130,1156]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.302" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" unit="in" value="13.0">13 in</quantity>
females, and 14 or 
<quantity box="[492,551,1170,1196]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.81" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" unit="in" value="15.0">15 in</quantity>
males) and the lack of submedial teeth on the anterior margin of the clypeus in males. In adults of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Ashmead" baseAuthorityYear="1887" box="[678,868,1210,1235]" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Leiophron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maculipennis">
<emphasis box="[678,868,1210,1235]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">L. maculipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, flagellomere 1 is short (2.3 times as long as wide), 4–5 preapical flagellomeres are as wide as or wider than long, and the flagellum is completely straw coloured. Freshly collected adults of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Ashmead" baseAuthorityYear="1887" box="[1085,1276,1290,1315]" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Leiophron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maculipennis">
<emphasis box="[1085,1276,1290,1315]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">L. maculipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are darker with a brown metasoma and the body is similarly coloured in both sexes. In 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Goulet &amp; Mason" authorityYear="2006" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Leiophron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">L. australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
flagellomere 1 is long (2.7–3.0 times as long as wide), no preapical flagellomeres are as wide as long, and the flagellum fades to brown in the apical third. Adults are paler with a straw coloured metasoma and the propodeum is brown in females and straw coloured in males.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[264,1325,284,1876]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
Adults of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Goulet &amp; Mason" authorityYear="2006" box="[442,582,1530,1555]" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Leiophron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis box="[442,582,1530,1555]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">L. australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differ from those of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Loan)" baseAuthorityName="Loan" baseAuthorityYear="1970" box="[861,1102,1530,1556]" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Leiophron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lygivorus">
<emphasis box="[861,1008,1530,1555]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">L. lygivorus</emphasis>
(Loan)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Gahan)" baseAuthorityName="Gahan" baseAuthorityYear="1913" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Leiophron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="uniformis">
<emphasis box="[1172,1322,1530,1555]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">L. uniformis</emphasis>
(Gahan)
</taxonomicName>
by the body colour pattern and forewing venation.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[264,1325,284,1876]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
Adults of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Goulet &amp; Mason" authorityYear="2006" box="[430,564,1610,1635]" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Leiophron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis box="[430,564,1610,1635]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">L. australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differ from those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Goulet &amp; Mason" authorityYear="2006" box="[811,920,1610,1635]" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Leiophron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="simoni">
<emphasis box="[811,920,1610,1635]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">L. simoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the forewing veins 1CU, m­cu and 2RS, the size of the radial cell relative to the stigmal length, notauli development, and the anterior mesoscutellar fovea proportions. A summary of measurements of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Goulet &amp; Mason" authorityYear="2006" box="[1188,1323,1690,1715]" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Leiophron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis box="[1188,1323,1690,1715]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">L. australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is given in Table 1. Because only 
<specimenCount box="[666,774,1730,1756]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" type="male">one male</specimenCount>
and 
<specimenCount box="[833,962,1730,1756]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" type="female">one female</specimenCount>
are known, the measurements are not discussed further.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="23" lastPageNumber="24" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" type="biology_ecology">
